    <title id="1">Link Aggregation Settings</title>
    <shortdesc id="2">The HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade supports several link aggregation (LAG)
        operational modes.</shortdesc>
    <prolog>
        <author id="3">Jim Owens</author>
        <author id="4">Pedro Sanchez</author>
        <author id="5">Tom Towle</author>
    </prolog>
    <refbody>
        <section id="section_N10027_N10024_N10001" id="6">
            <p id="7">If you select link aggregation (also known as Aggregate Ethernet) when
                configuring the management, infrastructure, or OAM networks, you can choose from the
                following operational modes. For more information, refer to the Linux kernel <xref format="html" href="https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/networking/bonding.txt" id="8" scope="external">Ethernet Bonding Driver</xref>
                documentation.</p>
            <!-- note id="note_N1003E_N1002C_N10029_N10001" id="70">
                <p id="71">Support for Balanced Round-Robin, Broadcast, Balance-tlb, and
                    Balanced-alb modes is planned for a future release.</p>
            </note -->
            <table frame="all" id="table_kb5_rwb_ln">
                <title id="9">Supported Link Aggregation Operational Modes</title>
                <tgroup cols="3">
                    <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                    <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2" colwidth="3.0*"/>
                    <colspec colname="newCol3" colnum="3" colwidth="2*"/>
                    <thead>
                        <row>
                            <entry id="10">
                                <p id="11">Mode</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="12">
                                <p id="13">Description</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="68">
                                <p id="69">Supported Interface Types</p>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <!-- row>
                            <entry id="14">
                                <p id="15">Balanced Round-Robin</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="16">
                                <p id="17">Provides aggregated bandwidth and fault
                                    tolerance. Data packets are transmitted in sequential order from
                                    the first available slave interface to the second.</p>
                            </entry>
                        </row -->
                        <row>
                            <entry id="18">
                                <p id="89">Active-backup</p>
                                <p id="90">(default value)</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="21">
                                <p id="22">Provides fault tolerance. Only one slave
                                    interface at a time is available. The backup slave interface
                                    becomes active only when the active slave interface fails.</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="70">
                                <p id="71">OAM, infrastructure, and data interfaces (compute nodes)</p>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry id="23">
                                <p id="24">Balanced XOR</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="25">
                                <p id="26">Provides aggregated bandwidth and fault
                                    tolerance. The same slave interface is used for each destination
                                    MAC address.</p>
                                <p id="27">This mode uses the default transmit policy, where
                                    the target slave interface is determined by calculating the
                                    source MAC address XOR'd with the destination MAC address,
                                    modulo 2.</p>
                                <p id="72">You can modify the transmit policy using the
                                    xmit-hash-policy option. For details, see <xref href="#jow1404333496893/xmit-hash-policy" id="74"/>.</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="76">
                                <p id="77">OAM, infrastructure, and data interfaces (compute nodes)</p>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <!-- row>
                            <entry id="30">
                                <p id="31">Broadcast</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="32">
                                <p id="33">Provides fault tolerance. Data packets are transmitted simultaneously to both
                  slave interfaces.</p>
                            </entry>
                        </row -->
                        <row>
                            <entry id="34">
                                <p id="35">802.3ad</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="36">
                                <p id="37">Provides aggregated bandwidth and fault
                                    tolerance. Implements dynamic link aggregation as per the IEEE
                                    802.3ad specification.</p>
                                <p id="73">You can modify the transmit policy using the
                                    xmit-hash-policy option. For details, see <xref href="#jow1404333496893/xmit-hash-policy" id="75"/>.</p>
                                <p id="78">In order to support booting over an aggregated management
                                    interface, the far-end switch ports must be configured in
                                    passive LACP mode.</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="79">
                                <p id="80">Internal management network</p>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <!-- row>
                            <entry id="38">
                                <p id="39">Balance-tlb (Adaptive transmit load balancing)</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="40">
                                <p id="41">Provides aggregated bandwidth and fault
                                    tolerance. Transmitted data traffic is distributed according to
                                    the current load, computed relative to the speed on each slave.
                                    If a receiving slave interface fails, the another slave
                                    interface takes over the orphan MAC addresses.</p>
                                <p id="42">Balance-tlb mode does not require any special switch support.</p>
                            </entry>
                        </row -->
                        <!-- row>
                            <entry id="43">
                                <p id="44">Balance-alb (Adaptive load balancing)</p>
                            </entry>
                            <entry id="45">
                                <p id="46">Provides aggregated bandwidth and fault
                                    tolerance. Includes Balance-tlb mode, plus receive load
                                    balancing for IPV4 traffic, which is achieved by ARP
                                    negotiation. </p>
                                <p id="47">Balance-alb mode does not require any special switch support.</p>
                            </entry>
                        </row -->
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
